every once in a while I must speak here

00:13:21.690 --> 00:13:23.120
and the opportunity to make corrections

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:24.770
keeps us all on the same page.

00:13:24.770 --> 00:13:27.010
And please do keep any
feedback that you have

00:13:27.010 --> 00:13:29.803
about particular things I
cover here coming my way.

00:13:30.750 --> 00:13:33.710
There is so much interest in metabolism.

00:13:33.710 --> 00:13:37.690
We hear about having a
high or a low metabolism.

00:13:37.690 --> 00:13:38.920
There are some people out there

00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:41.190
who would like to reduce their metabolism.

00:13:41.190 --> 00:13:44.310
They simply can't eat enough
to maintain their weight.

00:13:44.310 --> 00:13:47.840
Most people, however, struggle
with the opposite issue.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:50.644
They struggle to maintain a healthy weight

00:13:50.644 --> 00:13:53.090
and/or their metabolism is too low.

00:13:53.090 --> 00:13:54.510
Now, there are a variety of reasons

00:13:54.510 --> 00:13:56.200
why metabolism can be low.

00:13:56.200 --> 00:13:59.280
Today, we are going to
talk about two hormones,

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:02.470
thyroid hormone and its related pathways

00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:05.790
and growth hormone and
it's related pathways,

00:14:05.790 --> 00:14:08.570
which arguably are the two hormones

00:14:08.570 --> 00:14:12.100
and two systems in the body
that are most significant

00:14:12.100 --> 00:14:15.083
for setting your overall
level of metabolism.

00:14:16.220 --> 00:14:17.290
Before we dive into those,

00:14:17.290 --> 00:14:20.900
I just want to cover a little
bit of what metabolism is.

00:14:20.900 --> 00:14:23.960
And I want to talk about
which organs in your body

00:14:23.960 --> 00:14:25.400
use the most energy.

00:14:25.400 --> 00:14:28.520
So metabolism is the
consumption of energy,

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:29.860
not necessarily eating,

00:14:29.860 --> 00:14:34.110
but it's the use of energy
in the cells of the body

00:14:34.110 --> 00:14:37.660
for growth of tissues,
for repair of tissues,

00:14:37.660 --> 00:14:41.820
and also just for day-to-day
maintenance of function.

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:43.450
A good example of maintenance of function

00:14:43.450 --> 00:14:44.730
would be your brain.

00:14:44.730 --> 00:14:46.840
Most of your metabolic needs,

00:14:46.840 --> 00:14:49.970
your so-called basal or
resting metabolic needs

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:52.840
are for your brain, for thinking.

00:14:52.840 --> 00:14:54.720
If you were to just sit in a bed all day

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:56.830
and do nothing but think,

00:14:56.830 --> 00:15:01.600
that consumes about 75%
of your metabolic needs.

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:03.850
Now, there's also moving around.

00:15:03.850 --> 00:15:07.580
If you have a job that
requires a lot of heavy labor

00:15:07.580 --> 00:15:09.440
or lifting things or you're a new parent

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:10.520
and you're carrying kids around

00:15:10.520 --> 00:15:11.660
and you're going up and down the stairs

00:15:11.660 --> 00:15:13.950
or back and forth to the refrigerator

00:15:13.950 --> 00:15:16.120
for formula, et cetera,

00:15:16.120 --> 00:15:18.810
well then you're burning more
energy, burning more calories.

00:15:18.810 --> 00:15:21.450
But even if you are
very physically active,

00:15:21.450 --> 00:15:23.990
unless you're an ultra
marathoner or a marathoner,

00:15:23.990 --> 00:15:27.720
chances are that 75%
of your metabolic needs

00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:29.560
are coming just from your brain.

00:15:29.560 --> 00:15:32.420
And that's because neurons
consume a lot of energy.

00:15:32.420 --> 00:15:35.260
Neurons, of course, are just
the nerve cells of your brain.

00:15:35.260 --> 00:15:39.690
So these two hormones, thyroid
hormone and growth hormone,

00:15:39.690 --> 00:15:42.920
we think of as related to
metabolism of things in the body,

00:15:42.920 --> 00:15:45.970
keeping body fat low, and
keeping muscles strong,

00:15:45.970 --> 00:15:48.830
and tendons strong and
repairing themselves, et cetera,

00:15:48.830 --> 00:15:52.020
but they are also key for brain function,

00:15:52.020 --> 00:15:54.330
for the ability to
maintain cognitive function

00:15:54.330 --> 00:15:55.810
throughout the lifespan.

00:15:55.810 --> 00:15:58.990
So the big theme I'd like to introduce

00:15:58.990 --> 00:16:03.400
is that metabolism isn't
just about losing weight

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:04.930
but having a high metabolism,

00:16:04.930 --> 00:16:06.660
provided it's not too high, is great.

00:16:06.660 --> 00:16:08.600
It means that you will
have more lean tissue,

00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:11.847
more bone and muscle and
less adipose tissue, fat.

00:16:11.847 --> 00:16:14.120
And we know that that's healthy.

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:16.360
How much fat and how much muscle?

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:17.290
Well, that varies,

00:16:17.290 --> 00:16:19.220
and the numbers on this
are always shifting.

00:16:19.220 --> 00:16:24.220
But in general, muscle
and its related tissues

00:16:25.350 --> 00:16:28.860
burns more energy than
does adipose tissue or fat.

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:31.470
And the water in your body
doesn't consume any energy.

00:16:31.470 --> 00:16:34.030
So metabolism can be increased

00:16:34.030 --> 00:16:36.380
simply by adding muscle to your body

00:16:36.380 --> 00:16:39.540
and reducing fat or adjusting
the ratio of the two.

00:16:39.540 --> 00:16:41.520
But regardless, even if
you're not interested

00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:44.590
in changing body composition,
these two hormones,

00:16:44.590 --> 00:16:46.160
thyroid hormone and growth hormone,

00:16:46.160 --> 00:16:49.560
are super important for
metabolism of all kinds,

00:16:49.560 --> 00:16:51.900
including tissue repair after injury,

00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:53.720
including maintaining cognitive function

00:16:53.720 --> 00:16:56.700
and well-being and the ability
to think clearly as you age,

00:16:56.700 --> 00:16:58.720
offsetting dementia and so forth.

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:03.720
So the big theme here really
includes the previous episodes.

00:17:04.070 --> 00:17:06.070
You don't have to have seen those episodes

00:17:06.070 --> 00:17:09.120
but for the last three
episodes and today as well,

00:17:09.120 --> 00:17:10.480
we've been talking about hormones,

00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:12.390
these substances that are
released from one location

00:17:12.390 --> 00:17:15.180
in the body that go and act
other locations in the body.

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:16.320
I'm going to tell you how that works

00:17:16.320 --> 00:17:17.900
for thyroid and growth hormone.

00:17:17.900 --> 00:17:20.610
But now that you've heard
about testosterone and estrogen

00:17:20.610 --> 00:17:24.030
and you're going to hear about
thyroid and growth hormone,

00:17:24.030 --> 00:17:29.030
I want you to realize that
there's a repeating logic.

00:17:29.350 --> 00:17:31.570
First of all, there are
neurons in your brain

00:17:31.570 --> 00:17:34.020
in an area called the hypothalamus,

00:17:34.020 --> 00:17:36.200
which just means it's
below the thalamus, hypo.

00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:37.360
It sits at the base of your brain,

00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:39.360
in the front, it's part of the forebrain.

00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:41.190
So it's more or less above
the roof of your mouth,

00:17:41.190 --> 00:17:43.020
maybe about a centimeter or so,

00:17:43.020 --> 00:17:46.050
and then about a centimeter
forward in most people.

00:17:46.050 --> 00:17:50.847
And neurons in the
hypothalamus release hormones

00:17:51.820 --> 00:17:54.300
that are called releasing hormones.

00:17:54.300 --> 00:17:56.980
So we've talked in previous episodes

00:17:56.980 --> 00:18:00.610
about, for instance,
gonadotropin-releasing hormone.

00:18:00.610 --> 00:18:03.190
So those are a little
neurons that then signal

00:18:03.190 --> 00:18:05.290
another brain area called the pituitary

00:18:05.290 --> 00:18:06.890
to release other hormones.

00:18:06.890 --> 00:18:09.070
Today, we're going to see this again.

00:18:09.070 --> 00:18:14.020
In the brain, you have neurons
that release thyrotropin

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:17.610
or thyroid-releasing hormone.

00:18:17.610 --> 00:18:19.860
You also have growth
hormone-releasing hormone.

00:18:19.860 --> 00:18:21.780
So anytime you hear releasing,

00:18:21.780 --> 00:18:25.220
chances are those are neurons
that are in your brain

00:18:25.220 --> 00:18:27.250
and they extend little wires we call axons

00:18:27.250 --> 00:18:30.110
into your pituitary and the pituitary

00:18:30.110 --> 00:18:32.570
releases a bunch of hormones
into the bloodstream.

00:18:32.570 --> 00:18:34.410
And the pituitary releases things

00:18:34.410 --> 00:18:37.580
that most often have the
name of stimulating hormone

00:18:37.580 --> 00:18:39.700
because they stimulate organs.

00:18:39.700 --> 00:18:42.440
So in keeping with the
theme of thyroid hormone,

00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:45.540
you have thyroid-releasing
hormone in the brain,

00:18:45.540 --> 00:18:49.630
tells the pituitary to release
thyroid-stimulating hormone

00:18:49.630 --> 00:18:52.570
and then the thyroid, which
we'll talk about in a moment,

00:18:52.570 --> 00:18:54.470
releases thyroid hormones.

00:18:54.470 --> 00:18:57.020
In the testosterone and estrogen episode,

00:18:57.020 --> 00:18:59.550
we talked about how you have
gonadotropin-releasing hormone,

00:18:59.550 --> 00:19:01.370
there's the releasing
again, up in the brain.

00:19:01.370 --> 00:19:04.100
Remember, releasing hormone
comes from the brain.

00:19:04.100 --> 00:19:06.460
Then you had things
like luteinizing hormone

00:19:06.460 --> 00:19:08.050
and follicle-stimulating hormone,

00:19:08.050 --> 00:19:10.090
which were in the pituitary
and those traveled

00:19:10.090 --> 00:19:11.520
to the ovaries or the testes

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:13.740
and acted on those tissues, okay?

00:19:13.740 --> 00:19:16.740
So please try and embed this logic.

00:19:16.740 --> 00:19:18.540
If you hear the word releasing hormone,

00:19:18.540 --> 00:19:21.710
it's coming from the brain,
and that makes it actionable

00:19:21.710 --> 00:19:24.610
in certain ways that
we'll return to later.

00:19:24.610 --> 00:19:27.800
In addition, the pituitary is letting go

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:29.380
of all these hormones into the bloodstream

00:19:29.380 --> 00:19:31.520
that are stimulating different tissues.

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:34.710
So for thyroid, it's
thyroid-stimulating hormone.

00:19:34.710 --> 00:19:35.900
And then it goes to the thyroid.

00:19:35.900 --> 00:19:39.210
And the thyroid is a little
butterfly-shaped gland

00:19:39.210 --> 00:19:41.240
that's right around the Adam's apple.

00:19:41.240 --> 00:19:43.580
If you want to see yours, not directly

00:19:43.580 --> 00:19:44.800
'cause it's got skin over it,

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:47.120
what you would do is
you'd take a sip of water,

00:19:47.120 --> 00:19:49.270
you'd look in the mirror
and you'd swallow.

00:19:50.120 --> 00:19:54.210
And the thing that moves up
and down, that is your thyroid.

00:19:54.210 --> 00:19:56.130
Now, some people call it your Adam's apple

00:19:56.130 --> 00:19:59.820
because it sits right near
this protrusion in the trachea,

00:19:59.820 --> 00:20:01.670
which is the Adam's apple.

00:20:01.670 --> 00:20:04.360
No matter, whether or
not you're male, female,

00:20:04.360 --> 00:20:06.550
or regardless of what your
chromosomal background is,

00:20:06.550 --> 00:20:08.450
everyone has an Adam's apple.

00:20:08.450 --> 00:20:10.100
It tends to be more pronounced in people

00:20:10.100 --> 00:20:12.380
that got a surge of testosterone
early in development

00:20:12.380 --> 00:20:15.650
because it has a testosterone
sensitivity to it.

00:20:15.650 --> 00:20:17.740
And that actually controls the timbre,

00:20:17.740 --> 00:20:20.230
the so-called deepness of the voice.

00:20:20.230 --> 00:20:23.570
So the thyroid gland sits right there

00:20:23.570 --> 00:20:25.560
and it's got four little bumps behind it

00:20:25.560 --> 00:20:27.010
called the parathyroid gland.

00:20:27.010 --> 00:20:30.500
And it releases two
hormones into the blood

00:20:30.500 --> 00:20:32.800
to stimulate different
tissues and their metabolism.

00:20:32.800 --> 00:20:35.430
And those hormones are called T4 and T3.

00:20:35.430 --> 00:20:36.640
So if this is already sounding

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:41.140
like a lot of information,
it's really easy, I promise.

00:20:41.140 --> 00:20:42.530
Releasing hormone comes from the brain.

00:20:42.530 --> 00:20:44.610
Stimulating hormone
comes from the pituitary.

00:20:44.610 --> 00:20:47.270
And in this case, we're
talking about the thyroid,

00:20:47.270 --> 00:20:50.040
binding up that stimulating
hormone and saying, oh,

00:20:50.040 --> 00:20:50.873
I need to release something.

00:20:50.873 --> 00:20:52.430
And it releases T4 and T3.

00:20:52.430 --> 00:20:53.263
And guess what?

00:20:53.263 --> 00:20:55.060
You can basically forget about T4.

00:20:55.060 --> 00:20:58.150
T4, it's not completely
inactive, it has some roles,

00:20:58.150 --> 00:21:01.040
but T3 is the one that's
more or less active.

00:21:01.040 --> 00:21:04.050
Now, what does thyroid hormone do?

00:21:04.050 --> 00:21:05.500
A lot of people think, oh, thyroid,

00:21:05.500 --> 00:21:07.920
it's like metabolism and
people who are hyperthyroidal

00:21:07.920 --> 00:21:09.640
have bulging eyes and are real thin

00:21:09.640 --> 00:21:11.880
and people who have
hypothyroid are overweight

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:15.290
and their eyes are like are, you know,

00:21:15.290 --> 00:21:16.420
half closed or something.

00:21:16.420 --> 00:21:18.840
And indeed thyroid hormone controls

00:21:18.840 --> 00:21:20.993
a lot of the features of
the face and the eyes.

00:21:20.993 --> 00:21:25.170
And it can control amounts of
adipose tissue and so forth.

00:21:25.170 --> 00:21:30.170
But the main role of
thyroid hormone, of T3,

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:32.870
is to promote metabolism.

00:21:32.870 --> 00:21:35.960
And that doesn't just mean
the consumption of energy,

00:21:35.960 --> 00:21:37.900
it means the utilization of energy,

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:40.290
including the buildup of tissues.

00:21:40.290 --> 00:21:43.700
So it acts on all sorts of
target tissues in the body.

00:21:43.700 --> 00:21:47.370
It acts on muscle, it acts on the liver,

00:21:47.370 --> 00:21:51.100
it acts on the cartilage,
it acts on the bone.

00:21:51.100 --> 00:21:53.460
And it's not just
involved in using energy,

00:21:53.460 --> 00:21:55.030
it's also converting energy.

00:21:55.030 --> 00:21:56.780
I do realize I said that twice.

00:21:56.780 --> 00:21:58.750
It's involved in taking fats

00:21:58.750 --> 00:22:01.010
and breaking them down into fatty acids

00:22:01.010 --> 00:22:03.480
and converting those into ATP,

00:22:03.480 --> 00:22:07.800
which is an important thing
for cells to use energy.

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:10.220
It's also involved in taking sugars

00:22:10.220 --> 00:22:12.170
and turning those into energy.

00:22:12.170 --> 00:22:15.600
And yes, it goes to adipose tissue to fat.

00:22:15.600 --> 00:22:17.490
We have different kinds of fat
that we'll talk about today

00:22:17.490 --> 00:22:18.580
but it goes to white fat

00:22:18.580 --> 00:22:21.960
and it liberates or helps
liberate some of the fats

00:22:21.960 --> 00:22:25.630
from those fat cells
and use them for energy.

00:22:25.630 --> 00:22:27.000
And this is why higher thyroid

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:29.400
is associated with leaner bodies.

00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:33.430
Lower thyroid is associated
with less lean bodies.

00:22:33.430 --> 00:22:37.620
So one thing that's absolutely
key and is actionable,

00:22:37.620 --> 00:22:42.400
we're right there already in
discussing tools is iodine.

00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:47.330
Iodine comes from things
in the ocean, right?

00:22:47.330 --> 00:22:50.190
And here are a couple of
interesting facts about iodine.

00:22:50.190 --> 00:22:51.660
And then we'll talk about whether or not

00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:55.010
you should be supplementing iodine or not.

00:22:55.010 --> 00:22:59.563
First of all, iodine is most common

00:23:00.480 --> 00:23:04.080
in sea salt, in kelp and in seaweed.

00:23:04.080 --> 00:23:07.020
And most people can get enough iodine

00:23:07.020 --> 00:23:10.773
from the food they eat and/or
the table salt they consume.

00:23:11.890 --> 00:23:14.640
Almost all table salt
from all over the world,

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:17.103
regardless of where you
are, contains iodine.

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:20.820
The thyroid needs iodine

00:23:20.820 --> 00:23:22.990
in order to produce thyroid hormone.

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:25.000
And you need sufficient
levels of thyroid hormone,

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.210
not too much, but you need it.

00:23:27.210 --> 00:23:30.580
So chances are you are
getting enough iodine.

00:23:30.580 --> 00:23:32.200
Although, you might not,

00:23:32.200 --> 00:23:34.610
especially those of you
following a particularly,

00:23:34.610 --> 00:23:36.070
quote, unquote, clean diet,

00:23:36.070 --> 00:23:38.330
might not be getting enough iodine.

00:23:38.330 --> 00:23:39.750
Here's the deal with iodine.

00:23:39.750 --> 00:23:42.340
Iodine combines with an amino acid

00:23:42.340 --> 00:23:45.430
that we've talked about
before called L-tyrosine.

00:23:45.430 --> 00:23:47.710
L-tyrosine comes from meat, from nuts.

00:23:47.710 --> 00:23:49.880
There are some plant-based
sources as well.

00:23:49.880 --> 00:23:52.770
It is the precursor to dopamine.

00:23:52.770 --> 00:23:56.220
But in the thyroid,
iodine combines or works

00:23:56.220 --> 00:24:01.220
with L-tyrosine to produce T3
and T4, the thyroid hormone.

00:24:01.260 --> 00:24:04.460
So you absolutely need sufficient iodine,

00:24:04.460 --> 00:24:06.920
you need sufficient L-tyrosine,

00:24:06.920 --> 00:24:08.230
and then you also need something else,

00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:09.270
which is called selenium.

00:24:09.270 --> 00:24:11.780
And we'll talk about selenium in a moment.

00:24:11.780 --> 00:24:14.940
So there's a condition that shows up

00:24:14.940 --> 00:24:16.490
in little pockets in the world.

00:24:16.490 --> 00:24:21.490
It's not super common, meaning
it's not very widespread,

00:24:21.600 --> 00:24:25.050
but in certain areas that
are far away from the ocean,

00:24:25.050 --> 00:24:27.160
at one point, this was historically

00:24:27.160 --> 00:24:30.030
in the Midwestern states
of the United States,

00:24:30.030 --> 00:24:32.550
in some mountain regions
of other countries,

00:24:32.550 --> 00:24:37.550
in some areas of Africa that
were far from the ocean,

00:24:38.200 --> 00:24:42.290
people would get extremely
swollen bulges in their necks.

00:24:42.290 --> 00:24:44.540
And this was called goiter.

00:24:44.540 --> 00:24:47.130
And the reason they were
getting those swollen bulges

00:24:47.130 --> 00:24:50.720
is because the thyroid
itself was hypertrophying.

00:24:50.720 --> 00:24:55.660
It was growing in an attempt
to churn out more thyroid.

00:24:56.850 --> 00:24:58.760
And because it was getting a lot

00:24:58.760 --> 00:25:01.863
of stimulating hormone from the pituitary.

00:25:03.320 --> 00:25:05.180
And I don't want to go
too far off track here

00:25:05.180 --> 00:25:06.860
but as you recall,

00:25:06.860 --> 00:25:09.700
the brain and the pituitary
are paying attention

00:25:09.700 --> 00:25:12.687
in a cellular sense to the
levels of hormones in the blood.

00:25:12.687 --> 00:25:14.780
And when those hormones get too high,

00:25:14.780 --> 00:25:16.330
they shut off the stimulating hormone,

00:25:16.330 --> 00:25:17.780
they shut down the signal to make more,

00:25:17.780 --> 00:25:19.060
kind of like a thermostat.

00:25:19.060 --> 00:25:20.820
When the levels are too low,

00:25:20.820 --> 00:25:22.900
like there's not enough
testosterone in the bloodstream

00:25:22.900 --> 00:25:24.020
or there's not enough estrogen,

00:25:24.020 --> 00:25:28.170
the brain will continue to push
out the signal to make more.

00:25:28.170 --> 00:25:31.670
Similarly, if there's not
enough thyroid circulating

00:25:31.670 --> 00:25:34.280
or there's not enough
iodine to make thyroid,

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:36.940
therefore not enough
thyroid hormone circulating,

00:25:36.940 --> 00:25:40.530
the thyroid gland itself
is not getting shut down.

00:25:40.530 --> 00:25:42.090
There's tons of stimulating hormone

00:25:42.090 --> 00:25:43.510
and releasing hormone
coming from the brain,

00:25:43.510 --> 00:25:44.620
like release, release, release,

00:25:44.620 --> 00:25:46.057
and there's no way they
can make thyroid hormone

00:25:46.057 --> 00:25:48.460
and so the gland just gets
bigger and bigger and bigger.

00:25:48.460 --> 00:25:49.920
And so people get goiter.

00:25:49.920 --> 00:25:54.260
This is one of the reasons why
table salt has iodine in it.

00:25:54.260 --> 00:25:55.230
Although there are other foods

00:25:55.230 --> 00:25:57.460
that have iodine in it as well.

00:25:57.460 --> 00:26:00.390
So how much iodine do you need?

00:26:00.390 --> 00:26:02.440
Well, you don't need a whole lot.

00:26:02.440 --> 00:26:06.170
Some people who are hypothyroidal might,

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:07.130
and I want to emphasize might,

00:26:07.130 --> 00:26:08.820
you absolutely should talk to your doctor.

00:26:08.820 --> 00:26:10.010
This is a serious matter.

00:26:10.010 --> 00:26:12.140
Anytime you're talking about hormones

00:26:12.140 --> 00:26:13.900
or manipulating levels of thyroid,

00:26:13.900 --> 00:26:15.730
you absolutely want to
talk to your doctor.

00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:18.370
Some people benefit from
supplementing iodine.

00:26:18.370 --> 00:26:19.960
It is contained in most salts.

00:26:19.960 --> 00:26:23.720
It's in Himalayan salt,
not always, but often.

00:26:23.720 --> 00:26:25.990
I know these days, there's
a lot of excitement

00:26:25.990 --> 00:26:28.040
about pink salts and sea salts and what,

00:26:28.040 --> 00:26:29.920
you know, they're kind
of artisan salt thing

00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:33.450
has kind of taken off in the
foodie land, which is great.

00:26:33.450 --> 00:26:35.420
Some of them are actually quite tasty.

00:26:35.420 --> 00:26:39.240
You can just take it directly
if you like the taste of salt.

00:26:39.240 --> 00:26:41.290
But iodine can be supplemented

00:26:41.290 --> 00:26:43.970
through things like kelp and
seaweed and kelp tablets.

00:26:43.970 --> 00:26:47.100
Now, if you are hyperthyroidal,
you make too much thyroid,

00:26:47.100 --> 00:26:48.820
that actually can be a problem.

00:26:48.820 --> 00:26:51.300
So really, the best way to figure this out

00:26:51.300 --> 00:26:55.100
is to get your blood levels
tested of thyroid hormone.

00:26:55.100 --> 00:26:59.010
But there's so much iodine in the ocean

00:26:59.010 --> 00:27:01.550
that believe it or not people
that live near the coast

00:27:01.550 --> 00:27:03.570
can actually just absorb
it through the air,

00:27:03.570 --> 00:27:05.360
just by breathing ocean air.

00:27:05.360 --> 00:27:08.500
So that gives you a sense
of just how little iodine

00:27:08.500 --> 00:27:10.700
you actually need to
consume in food or in salt.

00:27:10.700 --> 00:27:12.290
So if you're within a
few miles of the ocean

00:27:12.290 --> 00:27:13.760
or you visit the ocean from time to time,

00:27:13.760 --> 00:27:15.620
you're probably getting plenty.

00:27:15.620 --> 00:27:17.550
It does have to come
together, as I mentioned,

00:27:17.550 --> 00:27:18.910
with L-tyrosine,

00:27:18.910 --> 00:27:21.853
and this is why foods
that contain L-tyrosine,

00:27:22.740 --> 00:27:25.993
and provided that you have
sufficient iodine in your diet,

00:27:26.950 --> 00:27:30.030
and if you have sufficient
selenium in your diet,

00:27:30.030 --> 00:27:32.640
does serve to increase your metabolism.

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:36.910
And that again is for the
growth and repair of tissues.

00:27:36.910 --> 00:27:38.600
And that's really important.

00:27:38.600 --> 00:27:40.550
It's not just about keeping
your metabolism high

00:27:40.550 --> 00:27:42.950
so that you can be on
the leaner side of things

00:27:42.950 --> 00:27:45.130
or adjust your body weight, excuse me,

00:27:45.130 --> 00:27:47.800
your body composition
ratios the way you like.

00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:51.080
Repair of injuries,
repair of brain tissue,

00:27:51.080 --> 00:27:52.880
clearance of any damage from neurons,

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:55.480
clearance of any damage to the body

00:27:55.480 --> 00:27:57.210
is also going to depend on thyroid.

00:27:57.210 --> 00:27:59.870
Again, metabolism being this kind of rate

00:27:59.870 --> 00:28:02.470
of fuel consumption and
use in the body, generally,

00:28:02.470 --> 00:28:06.010
not just about body mass
indexes and things of that sort.

00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:08.840
So let's talk about selenium
because it's really important.

00:28:08.840 --> 00:28:10.810
And even though most
people are getting a lot

00:28:10.810 --> 00:28:12.763
of sufficient iodine,

00:28:13.690 --> 00:28:17.310
and most people are probably
getting enough L-tyrosine.

00:28:17.310 --> 00:28:21.560
I'm guessing most people may
not be getting enough selenium

00:28:21.560 --> 00:28:23.840
if their goal is to
increase thyroid hormone,

00:28:23.840 --> 00:28:26.100
at least that's what the literature says.

00:28:26.100 --> 00:28:28.520
Without going into the biochemistry,

00:28:28.520 --> 00:28:30.160
selenium is important in order

00:28:30.160 --> 00:28:32.830
for thyroid hormone to be made

00:28:32.830 --> 00:28:36.000
because of the way that
it allows L-tyrosine

00:28:36.840 --> 00:28:39.520
and iodine to interact.

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:44.150
And the thing is most people
aren't getting enough selenium

00:28:44.150 --> 00:28:46.080
because they don't eat foods
that are high in selenium.

00:28:46.080 --> 00:28:47.640
Now, how much selenium you need

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:48.920
will depend on where you live.

00:28:48.920 --> 00:28:50.970
It actually varies country by country.

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:52.370
Some countries I found

00:28:53.870 --> 00:28:56.180
say that you should get 100 micrograms,

00:28:56.180 --> 00:28:58.590
some say 200, some say 155.

00:28:58.590 --> 00:29:00.780
The average was about 155 micrograms,

00:29:00.780 --> 00:29:02.380
the countries I looked at.

00:29:02.380 --> 00:29:04.780
People who are trying to
increase thyroid levels

00:29:04.780 --> 00:29:07.010
might want to consume more selenium.

00:29:07.010 --> 00:29:08.550
And if you consume a vitamin, of course,

00:29:08.550 --> 00:29:11.350
you want to make sure if it has selenium

00:29:11.350 --> 00:29:12.920
that you're not overdoing it by consuming

00:29:12.920 --> 00:29:15.120
a lot of selenium rich foods either.

00:29:15.120 --> 00:29:17.380
But nonetheless, I think it's fair to say

00:29:17.380 --> 00:29:19.970
that most people probably could do well

00:29:19.970 --> 00:29:23.080
by ingesting slightly more
selenium than they currently are.

00:29:23.080 --> 00:29:26.260
Although, of course,
always talk to your doctor.

00:29:26.260 --> 00:29:28.080
Brazil nuts are the heavyweight champion

00:29:28.080 --> 00:29:30.470
of foods to get selenium from.

00:29:30.470 --> 00:29:32.690
It has very high
concentrations of selenium.

00:29:32.690 --> 00:29:35.640
In just six or eight Brazil nuts

00:29:35.640 --> 00:29:40.420
contain something like 550
micrograms of selenium.

00:29:40.420 --> 00:29:42.290
It's also present in fish.

00:29:42.290 --> 00:29:44.970
So certain fish like yellowfin tuna,

00:29:44.970 --> 00:29:48.180
although nowadays whenever
I mention tuna or shellfish,

00:29:48.180 --> 00:29:50.890
which is the other rich
source of selenium,

00:29:50.890 --> 00:29:53.660
people will tell me immediately

00:29:53.660 --> 00:29:55.240
there are all sorts of issues around farm,

00:29:55.240 --> 00:29:57.150
not farm, mercury, et cetera.

00:29:57.150 --> 00:30:00.250
So I've never particularly
liked eating fish

00:30:00.250 --> 00:30:01.650
'cause of the way it tastes.

00:30:01.650 --> 00:30:02.780
So that's why I avoid it.

00:30:02.780 --> 00:30:03.920
But for those of you that like it,

00:30:03.920 --> 00:30:05.430
I'm sure you're much more skilled

00:30:05.430 --> 00:30:08.610
in knowing which fish to buy
and which fish not to buy.

00:30:08.610 --> 00:30:12.830
Ham, of all things,
contains a lot of selenium,

00:30:12.830 --> 00:30:14.520
for whatever reason pork does.

00:30:14.520 --> 00:30:16.260
I'm not a big consumer of pork.

00:30:16.260 --> 00:30:18.760
Beef has some selenium,
but what's interesting

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:21.030
if you look at the sources,
you know, pork, beef,

00:30:21.030 --> 00:30:25.640
turkey, chicken, cottage
cheese, eggs, brown rice,

00:30:25.640 --> 00:30:29.070
what you want to understand
is that Brazil nuts,

00:30:29.070 --> 00:30:33.980
six to eight Brazil nuts has
550 micrograms of selenium.

00:30:33.980 --> 00:30:36.120
And all the other foods I mentioned

00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:37.710
at much greater portion size

00:30:37.710 --> 00:30:40.780
than equivalent to six
to eight Brazil nuts,

00:30:40.780 --> 00:30:44.100
either by volume or by calories,

00:30:44.100 --> 00:30:47.570
they have something like 30
to 50 micrograms of selenium.

00:30:47.570 --> 00:30:48.850
So if you're not eating Brazil nuts,

00:30:48.850 --> 00:30:50.450
I'm guessing most people aren't,

00:30:51.440 --> 00:30:54.160
and you're not eating a
lot of animal based foods,

00:30:54.160 --> 00:30:55.750
which I know many of you aren't,

00:30:55.750 --> 00:30:58.900
then you're probably not
getting enough selenium.

00:30:58.900 --> 00:31:01.350
And again, you can have
these levels measured

00:31:01.350 --> 00:31:04.350
or you can just check what
you're consuming and figure out

00:31:04.350 --> 00:31:06.860
whether or not you're meeting
the ration that you need

00:31:06.860 --> 00:31:09.900
in order to get healthy levels of thyroid.

00:31:09.900 --> 00:31:13.370
It is present in things
like mushrooms, but again,

00:31:13.370 --> 00:31:16.630
in a bowl of mushrooms, you
know, what is the equivalent

00:31:16.630 --> 00:31:19.610
to a bowl of mushroom is
12 micrograms of selenium.

00:31:19.610 --> 00:31:23.540
And if the daily ration is
something in 100 to 200 range,

00:31:23.540 --> 00:31:25.200
again, look it up for the area you are.

00:31:25.200 --> 00:31:27.850
You can see really quickly
why even though things

00:31:27.850 --> 00:31:30.040
like mushrooms and spinach
and milk and yogurt

00:31:30.040 --> 00:31:31.100
and lentils and cashews,

00:31:31.100 --> 00:31:33.380
and now we're into the vegetarian segment

00:31:33.380 --> 00:31:35.040
of the list that I constructed,

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:36.770
you're probably not
getting enough selenium.

00:31:36.770 --> 00:31:38.960
So it's kind of an interesting thing.

00:31:38.960 --> 00:31:40.050
If you're an experimenter

00:31:40.050 --> 00:31:42.160
and you get the clearance
from your doctor,

00:31:42.160 --> 00:31:43.970
you could try increasing
your selenium levels

00:31:43.970 --> 00:31:46.120
and see how that impacts your metabolism.

00:31:46.120 --> 00:31:50.090
Again, Brazil nuts are probably
going to be the most direct way

00:31:50.090 --> 00:31:52.050
to get sufficient selenium levels

00:31:52.050 --> 00:31:54.200
but because levels are
so high in Brazil nuts,

00:31:54.200 --> 00:31:56.700
it also means that you
could overdo it as well.

00:31:56.700 --> 00:32:00.700
I'm not really aware of
what the consequences are

00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:04.370
of getting too much selenium,
although you can get too much

00:32:04.370 --> 00:32:07.490
of anything and I'm guessing
those consequences aren't good.

00:32:07.490 --> 00:32:10.640
I also want to mention that for children,

00:32:10.640 --> 00:32:13.710
their daily requirements
of selenium are much lower,

00:32:13.710 --> 00:32:18.710
as low as 30 or 40 micrograms
for kids 14 years or younger.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:22.000
And in some areas, I really
want to underscore this,

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:25.140
the amount of selenium
that's recommended daily

00:32:25.140 --> 00:32:28.090
is as low as 55 micrograms.

00:32:28.090 --> 00:32:30.190
So it's not that you should be shooting

00:32:30.190 --> 00:32:33.200
for thousands or even
high levels of hundreds

00:32:33.200 --> 00:32:34.810
of micrograms of selenium.

00:32:34.810 --> 00:32:37.310
And again, that's
micrograms, not milligrams.

00:32:37.310 --> 00:32:38.640
So again, look into what you need

00:32:38.640 --> 00:32:40.730
but if you're somebody who's interested

00:32:40.730 --> 00:32:45.730
in keeping thyroid function
healthy and productive,

00:32:45.750 --> 00:32:47.810
then you certainly want to make sure

00:32:47.810 --> 00:32:48.950
you're getting enough iodine,

00:32:48.950 --> 00:32:50.810
you're getting enough selenium

00:32:50.810 --> 00:32:52.630
and you're getting enough L-tyrosine.

00:32:52.630 --> 00:32:54.090
And it's interesting
when you start looking

00:32:54.090 --> 00:32:56.980
at the various foods, especially
highly processed foods,

00:32:56.980 --> 00:32:58.140
then you start to realize

00:32:58.140 --> 00:33:01.560
that perhaps many people,
maybe you, are not.

00:33:01.560 --> 00:33:05.160
Not incidentally, selenium
has some other effects

00:33:05.160 --> 00:33:07.440
on health that can be quite positive.

00:33:07.440 --> 00:33:09.200
And even though these
don't relate to thyroid

00:33:09.200 --> 00:33:11.140
or growth hormone function specifically,

00:33:11.140 --> 00:33:13.310
I think you might want to know about them,

00:33:13.310 --> 00:33:15.390
given that we're on the topic of selenium.

00:33:15.390 --> 00:33:17.720
The first is that there are three studies,

00:33:17.720 --> 00:33:21.380
all of which showed very high efficacy

00:33:21.380 --> 00:33:24.130
for reducing the risk of
something called preeclampsia,

00:33:25.360 --> 00:33:26.560
excuse me, preeclampsia.

00:33:27.840 --> 00:33:30.820
Preeclampsia is seizures that are related

00:33:30.820 --> 00:33:32.600
to blood pressure issues during

00:33:32.600 --> 00:33:36.240
or around the delivery of a new baby.

00:33:36.240 --> 00:33:38.890
And actually, it's a rare-ish condition

00:33:38.890 --> 00:33:41.410
but it actually can be quite deadly.

00:33:41.410 --> 00:33:44.880
And so the fact that selenium is important

00:33:44.880 --> 00:33:47.840
for offsetting preeclampsia
risk is interesting.

00:33:47.840 --> 00:33:49.490
I don't know the exact mechanism

00:33:49.490 --> 00:33:51.510
and I'm guessing there are
only a few of you out there

00:33:51.510 --> 00:33:55.200
that are either pregnant or
thinking of conceiving soon,

00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:56.490
but that's worth noting.

00:33:56.490 --> 00:33:59.590
Obviously, anything related
to pregnancy or lactation,

00:33:59.590 --> 00:34:01.770
especially talk to your doctor.

00:34:01.770 --> 00:34:03.900
I'm guessing that selenium is probably

00:34:03.900 --> 00:34:05.590
in a lot of prenatal formulas

00:34:05.590 --> 00:34:10.570
but that's one clear benefit
of having sufficient selenium.

00:34:10.570 --> 00:34:13.220
The other is a reduced
prostate cancer risk.

00:34:13.220 --> 00:34:16.140
There's a study showing that
having sufficient selenium

00:34:16.140 --> 00:34:18.203
can reduce prostate cancer risk.

00:34:19.110 --> 00:34:21.150
And there is some evidence

00:34:21.150 --> 00:34:24.260
that if you consume foods
from areas with soil

00:34:24.260 --> 00:34:26.810
that's low in selenium,
that can be a problem.

00:34:26.810 --> 00:34:29.320
And last episode, we talked
about all these issues related

00:34:29.320 --> 00:34:33.033
to soil quality, things that
are making their way into food

00:34:33.033 --> 00:34:36.043
that are disrupting hormones and so forth.

00:34:36.990 --> 00:34:40.300
But having sufficient selenium from food

00:34:40.300 --> 00:34:43.640
could offset the low content in any soil.

00:34:43.640 --> 00:34:46.840
And so that apparently can
reduce prostate cancer risk.

00:34:46.840 --> 00:34:47.770
It's a minor effect

00:34:47.770 --> 00:34:50.100
but it's a statistically significant one.

00:34:50.100 --> 00:34:52.470
And the other one is a reduction in acne,

00:34:52.470 --> 00:34:53.620
which is interesting.

00:34:53.620 --> 00:34:55.730
I'm guessing that that probably has to do

00:34:55.730 --> 00:34:57.260
with the thyroid hormone pathway

00:34:57.260 --> 00:35:01.110
because of the way thyroid
hormone can impact the liver.

00:35:01.110 --> 00:35:02.910
And it turns out that the liver

00:35:02.910 --> 00:35:05.910
and various biochemical reactions

00:35:05.910 --> 00:35:08.420
in the liver can impact acne.

00:35:08.420 --> 00:35:10.750
And that's probably an
episode all into itself

00:35:10.750 --> 00:35:13.120
but those are just some
additional benefits

00:35:13.120 --> 00:35:15.220
of getting a sufficient selenium.

00:35:15.220 --> 00:35:17.070
Okay, so we're already deep into tools

00:35:17.070 --> 00:35:20.970
related to making sure that
you have sufficient selenium,

00:35:20.970 --> 00:35:24.430
iodine, and L-tyrosine
in order to make enough

00:35:24.430 --> 00:35:28.660
thyroid hormones that can
support your metabolic processes

00:35:28.660 --> 00:35:30.500
in your liver, your muscles, your tendons,

00:35:30.500 --> 00:35:33.700
for whatever purpose,
keeping your metabolism high,

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:37.510
for body composition
reasons or for healing,

00:35:37.510 --> 00:35:39.830
for keeping your brain working well.

00:35:39.830 --> 00:35:42.580
Earlier I mentioned, there are people

00:35:42.580 --> 00:35:44.720
who are following very clean diets.

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:47.410
So these are people that
consume no processed foods.

00:35:47.410 --> 00:35:48.920
You know, any starch they might eat

00:35:48.920 --> 00:35:51.550
is going to be maybe a rice or a grain

00:35:51.550 --> 00:35:54.920
or any protein they might consume

00:35:54.920 --> 00:35:56.910
is going to be either from, let's hope,

00:35:56.910 --> 00:36:00.010
from humanely raised animal sources

00:36:00.010 --> 00:36:02.480
or maybe they're pure plant-based.

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:05.140
Believe it or not, those folks

00:36:05.140 --> 00:36:08.930
are actually very
susceptible to low iodine

00:36:08.930 --> 00:36:13.770
because it turns out that
diets that are very meat rich

00:36:13.770 --> 00:36:15.320
and don't have many vegetables,

00:36:15.320 --> 00:36:18.150
as well as diets that
are very vegetable rich

00:36:18.150 --> 00:36:21.040
but don't have many meats or salts

00:36:22.480 --> 00:36:25.330
are at risk of lowering thyroid hormone

00:36:25.330 --> 00:36:27.930
by way of the iodine
pathway and other pathways.

00:36:27.930 --> 00:36:30.740
And so let me try and
simplify this for you.

00:36:30.740 --> 00:36:32.810
Chances are if people are
doing the all-meat diet,

00:36:32.810 --> 00:36:34.950
they're not sprinkling, they're
not wrapping those steaks

00:36:34.950 --> 00:36:37.230
in seaweed and they may

00:36:37.230 --> 00:36:40.270
or may not be supplementing with iodine.

00:36:40.270 --> 00:36:43.040
Chances are they're probably
consuming iodine salt

00:36:43.040 --> 00:36:45.440
but their requirements go up

00:36:45.440 --> 00:36:46.880
if they're not consuming vegetables.

00:36:46.880 --> 00:36:49.420
People who are consuming
vegetables is kind of interesting.

00:36:49.420 --> 00:36:50.253
We always hear

00:36:50.253 --> 00:36:52.520
that we should have our
cruciferous vegetables

00:36:52.520 --> 00:36:53.740
and those are so important

00:36:53.740 --> 00:36:56.090
but there are actually substances,

00:36:56.090 --> 00:37:00.810
compounds within high quality
cruciferous vegetables

00:37:00.810 --> 00:37:03.700
that can interfere with
thyroid hormone function.

00:37:03.700 --> 00:37:06.010
So if you're eating a lot of that stuff,

00:37:06.010 --> 00:37:08.670
a lot of cabbages and
just look up your other,

00:37:08.670 --> 00:37:10.640
I think broccoli is a
cruciferous vegetable,

00:37:10.640 --> 00:37:11.960
and I won't read off the whole list,

00:37:11.960 --> 00:37:13.890
you could just put into the internet.

00:37:13.890 --> 00:37:16.140
But we're always told to eat a lot

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:18.570
of the dark, leafy green stuff.

00:37:18.570 --> 00:37:20.510
Well, unless that dark, leafy green stuff

00:37:20.510 --> 00:37:23.590
is kelp or seaweed,

00:37:23.590 --> 00:37:26.960
chances are that we're
not getting enough iodine

00:37:26.960 --> 00:37:29.390
unless we're adding salt to our food.

00:37:29.390 --> 00:37:31.860
And chances are that we may be lowering

00:37:31.860 --> 00:37:33.950
the total amount of
thyroid that we're making,

00:37:33.950 --> 00:37:37.950
as well as the fact that
in plant-rich diets,

00:37:37.950 --> 00:37:39.710
it's hard to get enough L-tyrosine

00:37:39.710 --> 00:37:42.300
and I don't want, you know,
I'm not here to inflame

00:37:42.300 --> 00:37:45.070
any of the vegans or the carnivore folks.

00:37:45.070 --> 00:37:47.380
I don't take a stance
either way on any of that.

00:37:47.380 --> 00:37:49.970
I'm just learning, trying
to report the science.

00:37:49.970 --> 00:37:52.740
The point I want to make is
your health is important.

00:37:52.740 --> 00:37:54.730
So if you are purely plant-based

00:37:54.730 --> 00:37:56.440
and you're eating a lot
of cruciferous vegetables,

00:37:56.440 --> 00:37:58.240
make sure you're getting enough iodine.

00:37:58.240 --> 00:38:00.410
It does seem like the
cruciferous vegetables

00:38:00.410 --> 00:38:03.510
can increase the need for further iodine.

00:38:03.510 --> 00:38:06.173
And same thing if you're
purely on this all-meat diet

00:38:06.173 --> 00:38:10.000
or your keto, and you're not
ingesting many vegetables.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:13.120
So I always thought that the
cleaner the diet, the better,

00:38:13.120 --> 00:38:15.030
but it turns and probably that's true

00:38:15.030 --> 00:38:19.130
from the standpoint of, you
know, hormone regulation,

00:38:19.130 --> 00:38:22.720
you know, estrogen and
testosterone and other hormones.

00:38:22.720 --> 00:38:25.510
The highly processed
foods really are terrible.

00:38:25.510 --> 00:38:27.110
There's so much evidence for that.

00:38:27.110 --> 00:38:30.760
The phthalates in plastics
and the processed foods

00:38:30.760 --> 00:38:31.670
and the emulsifiers,

00:38:31.670 --> 00:38:33.870
all this stuff we talked
about previous episode,

00:38:33.870 --> 00:38:36.410
but it does seem to be that people

00:38:36.410 --> 00:38:40.190
that are not getting enough
iodine for whatever reason,

00:38:40.190 --> 00:38:44.320
really need to check out whether
or not their iodine levels

00:38:44.320 --> 00:38:46.330
need to be increased because of the fact

00:38:46.330 --> 00:38:49.324
that they're consuming so
many plants or so many meats

00:38:49.324 --> 00:38:50.540
and in some cases,

00:38:50.540 --> 00:38:52.750
plants that actually
lower thyroid hormone.

00:38:52.750 --> 00:38:55.460
And not to beat a dead horse or cabbage,

00:38:55.460 --> 00:38:58.490
but there are a number of
things that iodine can do

00:38:58.490 --> 00:39:01.000
that are positive that are sort of,

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.190
they're related to thyroid, not directly,

00:39:03.190 --> 00:39:05.400
they're kind of offshoots
of the thyroid pathway

00:39:05.400 --> 00:39:07.990
on their downstream of it, we would say,

00:39:07.990 --> 00:39:10.410
in terms of how they
impact metabolic function.

00:39:10.410 --> 00:39:12.310
One of those is to reduce something

00:39:12.310 --> 00:39:13.930
called c-reactive protein.

00:39:13.930 --> 00:39:16.950
Some of you may have heard
of CRP or c-reactive protein.

00:39:16.950 --> 00:39:18.990
C-reactive protein is
something that you want to keep

00:39:18.990 --> 00:39:20.930
at modestly low levels.

00:39:20.930 --> 00:39:23.220
It's associated with
inflammation and various forms

00:39:23.220 --> 00:39:26.620
of heart disease and even eye
disease, macular degeneration.

00:39:26.620 --> 00:39:30.100
So it does appear that
iodine supplementation

00:39:30.100 --> 00:39:34.690
or getting sufficient iodine
from food, either works,

00:39:34.690 --> 00:39:39.360
is associated with reduced
levels of c-reactive protein

00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:41.610
in the blood and an
anti-inflammatory effect.

00:39:41.610 --> 00:39:44.010
And the anti-inflammatory
effect brings us back

00:39:44.010 --> 00:39:45.810
to our old friend, interleukin 6.

00:39:45.810 --> 00:39:48.480
Remember, they're these
inflammatory cytokines.

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:50.180
They have many, many names

00:39:50.180 --> 00:39:52.020
because there are many, many of them.

00:39:52.020 --> 00:39:55.320
Interleukin 10 is the one
that's anti-inflammatory.

00:39:55.320 --> 00:39:58.330
Interleukin 6 is the
one that's inflammatory.

00:39:58.330 --> 00:40:00.450
Anytime you see IL-6,

00:40:00.450 --> 00:40:03.170
that usually means that there's
an inflammatory response,

00:40:03.170 --> 00:40:06.330
there's a wound, there's
inflammation of the brain,

00:40:06.330 --> 00:40:09.170
somebody is either sleep
deprived or had a brain injury

00:40:09.170 --> 00:40:12.190
or they're dealing with
some sort of infection.

00:40:12.190 --> 00:40:15.130
IL-6 is kind of a
catch-all for inflammation.

00:40:15.130 --> 00:40:18.070
And it does appear that
iodine supplementation

00:40:18.070 --> 00:40:22.130
can reduce circulating IL-6
associated with inflammation.

00:40:22.130 --> 00:40:23.590
So in that sense,

00:40:23.590 --> 00:40:26.340
iodine can have an
anti-inflammatory effect.

00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:29.680
So by now, it should be abundantly clear.

00:40:29.680 --> 00:40:31.230
If you care about thyroid hormone,

00:40:31.230 --> 00:40:33.960
if you care about the
pathways that it impacts

00:40:33.960 --> 00:40:36.530
like having a high level of metabolism,

00:40:36.530 --> 00:40:39.300
which I guess if for no
other reason is attractive

00:40:39.300 --> 00:40:40.580
'cause then you can eat more

00:40:40.580 --> 00:40:43.780
and still maintain a
healthy body composition,

00:40:43.780 --> 00:40:47.230
but also for brain health,
cognitive function,

00:40:47.230 --> 00:40:49.300
tissue repair, all that stuff,

00:40:49.300 --> 00:40:52.160
keeping c-reactive protein
low, keeping IL-6 low,

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:53.480
make sure you're getting enough iodine,

00:40:53.480 --> 00:40:55.240
selenium and L-tyrosine.

00:40:55.240 --> 00:40:57.477
If you're curious how
thyroid actually increases

00:40:57.477 --> 00:40:59.920
the metabolism, allows you
to eat more, et cetera.

00:40:59.920 --> 00:41:02.200
It relates to something
we covered last issue,

00:41:02.200 --> 00:41:03.690
which is glucose.

00:41:03.690 --> 00:41:05.860
Remember when you eat
something, blood sugar goes up,

00:41:05.860 --> 00:41:08.340
insulin is secreted from the pancreas

00:41:08.340 --> 00:41:10.470
and it makes sure that blood
glucose doesn't go too high,

00:41:10.470 --> 00:41:12.470
which can damage tissues or too low,

00:41:12.470 --> 00:41:14.133
which can make you hypoglycemic.

00:41:15.190 --> 00:41:17.810
Thyroid increases glucose uptake

00:41:17.810 --> 00:41:21.360
by various tissues, in
particular muscle and bone.

00:41:21.360 --> 00:41:23.720
It actually can increase
bone mineral density,

00:41:23.720 --> 00:41:24.830
which is a really good thing.

00:41:24.830 --> 00:41:27.190
As you get older, injuries,

00:41:27.190 --> 00:41:30.120
when I say older, I mean
basically 30 and older,

00:41:30.120 --> 00:41:32.840
the reason you can recover
more quickly from injuries

00:41:32.840 --> 00:41:36.330
if you have a healthy thyroid
and healthy thyroid pathways

00:41:36.330 --> 00:41:38.740
is because you can consume energy.

00:41:38.740 --> 00:41:41.800
That energy is diverted toward bone repair

00:41:41.800 --> 00:41:43.960
and muscle repair and cartilage repair.

00:41:43.960 --> 00:41:47.810
And so the way it does this
again is by increasing ATP.

00:41:47.810 --> 00:41:52.030
But the whole idea here is that iodine,

00:41:52.030 --> 00:41:55.420
selenium, L-tyrosine, allow
thyroid to be at healthy levels

00:41:55.420 --> 00:41:58.760
so that thyroid then can
take glucose in the blood

00:41:58.760 --> 00:42:01.330
and divert it to tissues
for it to be used,

00:42:01.330 --> 00:42:02.580
in particular your brain.

00:42:02.580 --> 00:42:05.410
And that's why these things
that we're talking about,

00:42:05.410 --> 00:42:07.750
supplementing or getting from food,

00:42:07.750 --> 00:42:10.940
can actually improve or
support brain function.

00:42:10.940 --> 00:42:11.970
People are always asking me,

00:42:11.970 --> 00:42:14.870
what is the food that I
should eat for my brain?

00:42:14.870 --> 00:42:16.470
Like, are blueberries good for your brain?

00:42:16.470 --> 00:42:18.860
Or they do ask me, are
walnuts good for your brain

00:42:18.860 --> 00:42:20.230
'cause it looks like a brain?

00:42:20.230 --> 00:42:21.580
We talked about that earlier.

00:42:21.580 --> 00:42:24.240
The fact of the matter is what you need

00:42:24.240 --> 00:42:26.580
are nutrients that support hormones

00:42:26.580 --> 00:42:28.770
and biological pathways
that support the brain.

00:42:28.770 --> 00:42:29.980
That's the way to think about it.

00:42:29.980 --> 00:42:31.210
And I realized when people ask,

00:42:31.210 --> 00:42:32.700
what should I eat to support my brain?

00:42:32.700 --> 00:42:35.760
That's basically what
they're asking in short form.

00:42:35.760 --> 00:42:39.020
So keeping your thyroid hormone healthy

00:42:39.020 --> 00:42:41.890
at healthy levels that is,
is going to be terrific

00:42:41.890 --> 00:42:44.820
for your brain because
75% of your metabolism

00:42:44.820 --> 00:42:45.700
is from your brain.

00:42:45.700 --> 00:42:47.520
The ability of your brain to use glucose

00:42:47.520 --> 00:42:50.060
or ketones for that matter
is going to be aided

00:42:50.060 --> 00:42:52.230
by having healthy thyroid.

00:42:52.230 --> 00:42:55.170
So do the things, take
the things, eat the things

00:42:55.170 --> 00:42:56.380
that are going to allow you

00:42:56.380 --> 00:42:59.010
to have healthy levels of thyroid hormone.

00:42:59.010 --> 00:43:00.840
I'm sure a number of you
are out there wondering,

00:43:00.840 --> 00:43:03.320
do I have healthy levels
of thyroid hormone?

00:43:03.320 --> 00:43:04.890
Those can be measured from the blood.

00:43:04.890 --> 00:43:08.550
There are some telltale signs
of having really high thyroid

00:43:08.550 --> 00:43:11.590
or really low thyroid, and I
could start listing those off.

00:43:11.590 --> 00:43:13.580
They're easy to find online as well.

00:43:13.580 --> 00:43:15.630
Things like bulging eyes,

00:43:15.630 --> 00:43:19.100
inability to maintain
weight, shaky, anxiety,

00:43:19.100 --> 00:43:21.720
that's kind of hyperthyroidal,
thinning of hair,

00:43:21.720 --> 00:43:23.498
this kind of thing.

00:43:23.498 --> 00:43:26.750
I don't want to get into
diagnosing hypothyroidism

00:43:26.750 --> 00:43:27.880
and hyperthyroidism.

00:43:27.880 --> 00:43:29.780
It's just impossible 'cause you're there

00:43:29.780 --> 00:43:31.590
and I'm here and we're kind
of shouting back and forth

00:43:31.590 --> 00:43:34.430
through a tunnel of video and comments.

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:37.160
If you're concerned about
having excessively high

00:43:37.160 --> 00:43:39.640
or excessively low levels
of thyroid hormone,

00:43:39.640 --> 00:43:42.000
absolutely look up what the symptoms are.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:43.930
Talk to your physician.

00:43:43.930 --> 00:43:45.600
And there are a number of good treatments.

00:43:45.600 --> 00:43:47.400
I didn't talk about prescription drugs

00:43:47.400 --> 00:43:51.770
that can improve symptoms
related to hypo or hyperthyroid.

00:43:51.770 --> 00:43:55.240
Of course, they have synthesized thyroid.

00:43:55.240 --> 00:43:56.610
So if you don't make enough thyroid,

00:43:56.610 --> 00:43:59.200
you can take thyroid,
it's by prescription.

00:43:59.200 --> 00:44:01.220
If you have too much thyroid,

00:44:01.220 --> 00:44:03.670
sometimes they'll take
out the thyroid gland

00:44:03.670 --> 00:44:05.620
or they can administer drugs

00:44:05.620 --> 00:44:09.290
that will either block
receptors or will interfere

00:44:09.290 --> 00:44:11.420
with some of the pathways from the brain

00:44:11.420 --> 00:44:14.010
to the pituitary or from
the pituitary to the thyroid

00:44:14.010 --> 00:44:16.770
in order to adjust the
thyroid hormone that way.

00:44:16.770 --> 00:44:21.140
So there are the big guns
in terms of the treatments

00:44:21.140 --> 00:44:23.140
for different thyroid disorders

00:44:23.140 --> 00:44:25.050
but we're not talking
about thyroid disorders,

00:44:25.050 --> 00:44:28.370
we're talking about how to get
and maintain thyroid levels

00:44:28.370 --> 00:44:31.340
in healthy ranges and some
straightforward ways to do that

00:44:31.340 --> 00:44:33.770
through diet and supplementation.

00:44:33.770 --> 00:44:35.200
There's also a lot of evidence

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:36.520
that for people who menstruate,

00:44:36.520 --> 00:44:39.010
levels of thyroid hormone
can fluctuate dramatically

00:44:39.010 --> 00:44:40.580
across the menstrual cycle.

00:44:40.580 --> 00:44:43.860
So that's really going to be
a process of experimentation.

00:44:43.860 --> 00:44:45.940
I don't know that you could,

00:44:45.940 --> 00:44:49.560
you could, in theory, take
blood at different phases

00:44:49.560 --> 00:44:51.220
of your cycle and figure
out whether or not

00:44:51.220 --> 00:44:53.300
your thyroid hormone was
excessively high or low

00:44:53.300 --> 00:44:54.700
at different phases of the cycle.

00:44:54.700 --> 00:44:56.570
That's going to be pretty tough to do.

00:44:56.570 --> 00:44:57.960
If you have an endocrinologist

00:44:57.960 --> 00:45:00.250
that's willing to do
that with you, terrific.

00:45:00.250 --> 00:45:02.730
I think most people are
going to have to figure out

00:45:02.730 --> 00:45:04.650
how supplementing the sorts of things

00:45:04.650 --> 00:45:05.650
that we talked about before,

00:45:05.650 --> 00:45:07.570
or getting them from foods relates

00:45:07.570 --> 00:45:09.380
to different aspects of their cycle.

00:45:09.380 --> 00:45:12.310
In general, the first half of
the cycle before ovulation,

00:45:12.310 --> 00:45:14.830
people crave carbohydrates and sweets more

00:45:15.677 --> 00:45:18.570
and that makes total
sense based on the biology

00:45:18.570 --> 00:45:20.400
of the menstrual cycle.

00:45:20.400 --> 00:45:23.800
Thyroid hormone is going to go up as you,

00:45:23.800 --> 00:45:26.850
as anyone, male or female,
menstruating or not,

00:45:26.850 --> 00:45:29.560
increases more starchy carbohydrates.

00:45:29.560 --> 00:45:32.840
This is interesting because
ketogenic diets have been shown

00:45:32.840 --> 00:45:34.680
to slightly lower thyroid levels.

00:45:34.680 --> 00:45:37.990
And that makes sense
because in ketogenic diets,

00:45:37.990 --> 00:45:40.250
blood glucose levels are very low.

00:45:40.250 --> 00:45:43.940
And thyroid hormone is
secreted in large part

00:45:43.940 --> 00:45:48.090
in proportion to how much
glucose is in the bloodstream

00:45:48.090 --> 00:45:51.800
and how much that glucose,
excuse me, needs to be regulated.

00:45:51.800 --> 00:45:54.050
So I'm not trying to
demonize the ketogenic diet.

00:45:54.050 --> 00:45:56.410
I think it definitely has its place.

00:45:56.410 --> 00:45:58.670
There are 22 studies now

00:45:58.670 --> 00:46:01.940
showing that it can dramatically
reduce blood glucose.

00:46:01.940 --> 00:46:05.320
And about a third of those show
that thyroid hormone levels

00:46:05.320 --> 00:46:08.430
are slightly reduced,
sometimes significantly,

00:46:08.430 --> 00:46:12.560
if not more, in the ketogenic diet

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:16.120
that may explain, I want
to highlight may explain

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:19.320
the fact that when people go
back to a more traditional diet

00:46:19.320 --> 00:46:22.700
if they've been on a ketogenic
diet for a long time,

00:46:22.700 --> 00:46:26.010
that oftentimes they will
gain weight very quickly

00:46:26.010 --> 00:46:28.630
as they bring carbohydrates
back into their diet.

00:46:28.630 --> 00:46:29.500
Some people are cycling

00:46:29.500 --> 00:46:32.220
between ketogenic and non-ketogenic
every three, four days.

00:46:32.220 --> 00:46:33.540
So-called cyclical ketogenic diet.

00:46:33.540 --> 00:46:35.830
Some people are staying ketogenic
for long periods of time.

00:46:35.830 --> 00:46:37.450
Some people six days on, one day off.

00:46:37.450 --> 00:46:39.730
So there's a huge variation there.

00:46:39.730 --> 00:46:42.400
The point is that carbohydrates,

00:46:42.400 --> 00:46:43.860
starchy carbohydrates in particular,

00:46:43.860 --> 00:46:47.500
support the healthy
production of T3 and T4.

00:46:47.500 --> 00:46:50.540
And so if you're very low carbohydrate,

00:46:50.540 --> 00:46:53.110
you're going to have a
reduction in T3 and T4.

00:46:53.110 --> 00:46:55.210
And so if you're going
to bring carbohydrates

00:46:55.210 --> 00:46:56.360
back into your diet,

00:46:56.360 --> 00:46:57.790
then you might want to
do it more gradually.

00:46:57.790 --> 00:46:59.430
And for those of you that menstruate,

00:46:59.430 --> 00:47:01.550
and are craving carbohydrates

00:47:01.550 --> 00:47:02.740
in the early part of the cycle,

00:47:02.740 --> 00:47:06.000
that is actually associated
with having a healthy cycle.

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:09.960
If any of you have had a healthy
cycle on a ketogenic diet,

00:47:09.960 --> 00:47:10.850
that would be interesting.

00:47:10.850 --> 00:47:12.490
Maybe let me know through the comments

00:47:12.490 --> 00:47:14.430
or point me in the
direction of some research

00:47:14.430 --> 00:47:15.550
if you're aware of it.

00:47:15.550 --> 00:47:16.470
So as you can start to see,

00:47:16.470 --> 00:47:18.110
there's this really beautiful interplay

00:47:18.110 --> 00:47:19.230
between the different hormones,

00:47:19.230 --> 00:47:23.850
between insulin and glucose,
between estrogen and thyroid,

00:47:23.850 --> 00:47:28.090
between thyroid and blood
glucose and the ketogenic diet.

00:47:28.090 --> 00:47:29.800
It all starts to fit together

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:31.590
in ways that make a lot of sense

00:47:31.590 --> 00:47:33.680
once you understand just
kind of the core elements

00:47:33.680 --> 00:47:34.760
of what the hormones are

00:47:34.760 --> 00:47:37.030
and the variety of
tissues that they work on.

00:47:37.030 --> 00:47:38.130
The simple version of this

00:47:38.130 --> 00:47:41.410
is if you haven't had a
carbohydrate for a year,

00:47:41.410 --> 00:47:44.880
then your T3, T4 levels
are going to be pretty low.

00:47:44.880 --> 00:47:46.710
And I'm sure there's some
ketonistas out there.

00:47:46.710 --> 00:47:47.650
They're going to say, wait, no,

00:47:47.650 --> 00:47:50.080
thyroid hormone levels go up with keto.

00:47:50.080 --> 00:47:52.670
That might be true for other reasons,

00:47:52.670 --> 00:47:55.650
indirect reasons related
to hormone pathways

00:47:55.650 --> 00:47:58.270
that are cascade from being in ketosis

00:47:58.270 --> 00:47:59.270
for long periods of time.

00:47:59.270 --> 00:48:00.103
Great.

00:48:00.103 --> 00:48:02.680
But for most people that don't
consume any carbohydrate,

00:48:02.680 --> 00:48:04.280
T3, T4 are going to go down.

00:48:04.280 --> 00:48:06.530
And when they start to consume foods

00:48:06.530 --> 00:48:08.950
that require thyroid metabolism

00:48:08.950 --> 00:48:11.720
in order to work with, to metabolize,

00:48:11.720 --> 00:48:14.860
then weight gain can
sometimes happen more quickly.

00:48:14.860 --> 00:48:16.550
So it's just something to consider.

00:48:16.550 --> 00:48:19.860
And it's something to work with carefully

00:48:19.860 --> 00:48:23.300
if you're going to be cyclic
ketogenic, long-term ketogenic.

00:48:23.300 --> 00:48:24.520
And if you're not ketogenic,

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:27.060
and you're consuming carbohydrates.

